{"key":"post-12892449","value":"<?xml version=\"1.0\"?>\n<post>\n<id>12892449</id>\n<content>There's some pretty bad info in this thread.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;A too wet or too dry substrate will cause the problems you're seeing with small size, and both give the same presentation.&amp;nbsp; You can judge substrate moisture content by picking it up.&amp;nbsp; If it's light, it's too dry, and if it weighs more than normal, it's too wet.&amp;nbsp; &lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Contrary to something else stated above, there is no such thing as excess light.&amp;nbsp; The curved stems and tiny caps indicate insufficient light.&amp;nbsp; Mushrooms derive energy from light and will generally turn and grow towards it, providing the light is intense enough.&amp;nbsp; Very small caps are also an indication of insufficient light.&lt;br /&gt;&lt;br /&gt;Another thing that will result in tiny mushrooms is if the pH of the substrate is way off.&amp;nbsp; Hopefully, you didn't lime the coir before using.&lt;br /&gt;RR</content>\n<name>RogerRabbit</name>\n<next>12892488</next>\n<prev>12891782</prev>\n<first>12891543</first>\n<last>12892488</last>\n<when>1279044215</when>\n<utime>07/13/10 09:03 PM</utime>\n</post>"}